---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import ADRBox from "../components/ADRBox.astro";
import DiscussOnGitHub from "../components/DiscussOnGitHub.astro";
import NewsletterCTA from "../components/NewsletterCTA.astro";

/* Long-form essay stub — placeholder body until the W1 draft lands.
 * The point of this page in this sprint is the *template*: post header,
 * lead paragraph, body with H2/H3, ADR Box, code block, end-of-post stack
 * (Discuss, Newsletter), prev/next navigation. Replace body when the real
 * essay is wired through MDX or a content collection. */

const title = "Why we are Wakir Labs";
const description =
  "Naming-as-methodology — five rounds, fifty candidates, one verifiable trail.";
---

<Base
  title={title}
  description={description}
  ogType="article"
  publishedTime="2026-05-03"
>
  <article class="essay">
    <header class="essay__header">
      <p class="essay__meta">
        <span>2026-05-XX</span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
        <span>brand &middot; methodology</span>
      </p>
      <h1 class="essay__title">{title}</h1>
      <p class="essay__lead">
        We picked a name the way we will pick everything else: by writing the
        decision down, signing it with a key, and stamping the signature into
        Bitcoin. The name is the first artifact of the methodology.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="essay__body">
      <h2>The question</h2>
      <p>
        Most company names are picked in a brainstorm and approved by a
        founder over coffee. That works fine right up until someone asks
        <em>why</em>. We wanted a record of the why &mdash; not because we
        expect challenge, but because the discipline of recording the why is
        the point of the company.
      </p>

      <p>
        The brief was simple: a name that means something in the language of
        the thing we build, that survives a trademark search, that sounds
        like an archive instead of a launch. Five rounds and fifty
        candidates later, the answer was a word from Arabic legal usage.
      </p>

      <ADRBox
        id="0018"
        title="Brand name"
        status="Accepted"
        decided="2026-05-02"
        summary="Wakir Labs &mdash; from Arabic wakīl, an appointed representative. Rejects pop-AI agent semantics in favor of legal-agent semantics."
        verifyUrl="https://opentimestamps.org/info?digest=…"
        verifyBlock="898241"
        verifyDate="2026-05-03"
        href="/decisions/0018-brand-name/"
      />

      <h2>How the trail works</h2>
      <p>
        Every decision lands as an ADR. Every commit on the repository
        carries a timestamp anchored in a Bitcoin block. The verification is
        public:
      </p>

      <pre><code class="language-bash">{`# In a clone of the repo:
ots verify -f <(git rev-parse 8aa88b9 | xxd -r -p) \\
  meta/timestamps/8aa88b9.ots`}</code></pre>

      <p>
        The output names the Bitcoin block that attests the commit existed
        at or before its mining time. No trust in us required &mdash; only
        in Bitcoin and the OpenTimestamps calendar servers, which only sign,
        never back-date.
      </p>

      <h2>What the name commits us to</h2>
      <p>
        <em>Wakil</em> in Arabic legal use means an appointed representative
        with bounded authority. That is the ontology of our framework: every
        agent is appointed, every agent has a defined scope, and the
        relationship is documented. The name is the mission statement
        compressed to two syllables.
      </p>

      <hr />
    </div>

    <DiscussOnGitHub
      href="https://github.com/wakir-labs/site/discussions"
      title={title}
    />

    <NewsletterCTA variant="inline" />

    <nav class="essay__nav" aria-label="Post navigation">
      <span>&larr; previous post</span>
      <span>next post &rarr;</span>
    </nav>
  </article>
</Base>
